+
+        <!-- i. WHY THIS MATTERED -->
+        <div class="case-section" id="latam-context">
+          <div class="num">i.</div>
+          <h2>Why this mattered</h2>
+
+          <div class="cs-disclaimer">Some business figures have been omitted / cannot be shared in actuality per confidentiality obligations.</div>
+
+          <p>
+            Latin America is one of the world's fastest-growing regions for crypto
+            adoption. According to Chainalysis, the region recorded over $562 billion
+            in on-chain transaction volume in 2023 — driven by high
+            <span class="term" data-def="A digital currency like USDT, pegged 1:1 to the US dollar. Widely used in high-inflation countries as an alternative to local currency.">stablecoin</span>
+            usage in high-inflation economies and growing retail participation across
+            Mexico, Colombia, and Brazil. Argentina, Venezuela, and Brazil
+            consistently rank in the global top 15 for crypto adoption per capita.
+          </p>
+          <p>
+            The macro case was strong: LatAm has a large
+            <span class="term" data-def="People without access to traditional bank accounts. In LatAm, roughly 45% of adults are underserved by traditional banking.">underbanked population</span>,
+            over $150 billion in annual remittances (where crypto offers a cheaper
+            and faster alternative), and high smartphone penetration — all driving
+            demand for accessible digital financial tools.
+          </p>
+          <p>
+            <strong>80% of our LatAm revenue came from just three countries:
+            Mexico, Argentina, and Colombia.</strong> Argentina was the standout —
+            local currency instability drives consistent demand for
+            dollar-denominated digital assets. Colombia was the fastest growing.
+          </p>
+          <p>
+            But we were losing market share to competitors who had already solved
+            what we hadn't. The market leader had <strong>6× our trading volume
+            in Mexico</strong> and Colombia. In Argentina the gap was smaller, but
+            a single competitor's Argentina revenue was still nearly <strong>3× ours</strong>.
+            Every major player offered instant bank transfers. We didn't.
+            That one gap was compounding.
+          </p>
+        </div>
+
+        <!-- ii. PROBLEM -->
+        <div class="case-section" id="latam-problem">
+          <div class="num">ii.</div>
+          <h2>Problem</h2>
+          <p>
+            To start investing on our platform, new users had to first fund their account.
+            In LatAm, the only option was
+            <span class="term" data-def="Peer-to-peer: buying directly from another user — like a marketplace. No bank or instant transfer. Each trade involves a real person on the other end.">P2P trading</span>
+            — a five-step manual process requiring interaction with a stranger,
+            payment proof uploads, and a manual fund release. For most first-time
+            users, this felt like too much to get through before ever placing a trade.
+          </p>
+          <p>The funnel confirmed two failure points:</p>
+
+          <div class="cs-funnel">
+            <div class="cs-funnel-step">
+              <div class="step-name">Sign-up</div>
+              <div class="step-status ok">✓ Healthy</div>
+              <div class="step-note">Middle of the pack vs. peer markets</div>
+            </div>
+            <div class="cs-funnel-step">
+              <div class="step-name">Identity check</div>
+              <div class="step-status ok">✓ Strong</div>
+              <div class="step-note">Best among comparable markets</div>
+            </div>
+            <div class="cs-funnel-step caution-step">
+              <div class="step-name">First deposit</div>
+              <div class="step-status caution">⚠ Below market</div>
+              <div class="step-note">P2P only — while competitors offered instant bank transfers</div>
+            </div>
+            <div class="cs-funnel-step problem-step">
+              <div class="step-name">First trade</div>
+              <div class="step-status warn">✗ Lowest</div>
+              <div class="step-note">Worst of all regions — users dropped off before trading</div>
+            </div>
+          </div>
+
+          <p>
+            Sign-up and identity checks were healthy. The breakdown started at
+            first deposit — where P2P put us at a structural disadvantage versus
+            every major competitor — and compounded through to first trade, where
+            users who did get through the P2P flow were already burnt out.
+            <strong>Both steps were the problem.</strong>
+          </p>
+        </div>
+
+        <!-- iii. RESEARCH & DECISIONS (merged) -->
+        <div class="case-section" id="latam-diagnosis">
+          <div class="num">iii.</div>
+          <h2>Research & decisions</h2>
+
+          <p>
+            I needed to understand why P2P wasn't working for new users.
+          </p>
+
+          <div class="cs-rpoints">
+            <div class="cs-rpoint">
+              <div class="cs-rpoint-icon">📊</div>
+              <div class="cs-rpoint-body">
+                <span class="cs-rpoint-title">What the data showed</span>
+                <p>
+                  First-deposit completion was below market because P2P was the
+                  <em>only</em> way to fund an account in LatAm — there was no
+                  alternative path for new users. And it wasn't just a deposit problem:
+                  less than 20% of users who completed their first deposit made a
+                  repeated trade within a month. We were losing users both at the
+                  deposit step and right after it.
+                </p>
+              </div>
+            </div>
+
+            <div class="cs-rpoint">
+              <div class="cs-rpoint-icon">🗣</div>
+              <div class="cs-rpoint-body">
+                <span class="cs-rpoint-title">50+ user interviews — MX · CO · AR</span>
+                <p>
+                  A clear pattern emerged: new users found P2P difficult to navigate and
+                  intimidating. Many had switched to using Bitso or other local exchanges
+                  just to onramp, then transferred funds back to us. We weren't the
+                  front door anymore — users were routing around us to get in.
+                </p>
+              </div>
+            </div>
+
+            <div class="cs-rpoint">
+              <div class="cs-rpoint-icon">🏆</div>
+              <div class="cs-rpoint-body">
+                <span class="cs-rpoint-title">Competitive landscape</span>
+                <p>
+                  Every major regional player had already solved this. Bitso ran on
+                  SPEI. Binance used local rails. Lemon and Ripio offered direct bank
+                  deposits. While they gave new users a frictionless path from local
+                  currency to crypto, we were asking ours to navigate a peer-to-peer
+                  marketplace first.
+                </p>
+
+                <div class="cs-compare" style="margin-top:18px;">
+                  <div class="cs-compare-col">
+                    <div class="cs-compare-header">
+                      <span class="cs-compare-title">P2P — Us</span>
+                      <span class="cs-compare-time">~40 min avg.</span>
+                    </div>
