+                      <div class="cs-compare-step"><span class="cs-step-n">2</span>Enter amount</div>
+                      <div class="cs-compare-step"><span class="cs-step-n">3</span>Complete bank transfer — funds credited automatically</div>
+                    </div>
+                  </div>
+                </div>
+              </div>
+            </div>
+          </div>
+
+          <p style="margin-top:28px;">
+            The direction was clear: we needed a native bank transfer flow.
+            The real question was <em>how</em> — without rebuilding the rails ourselves.
+            Three decisions defined the approach.
+          </p>
+
+          <div class="cs-decision">
+            <div class="decision-label">Decision 1 — Build vs. Partner</div>
+            <div class="decision-text">
+              Building our own fiat rails would mean banking licenses and regulatory
+              approvals in each market — easily 12–18 months per country.
+              <strong>We chose to partner</strong> with an existing payments aggregator
+              and reinvested that time into the user experience instead.
+            </div>
+          </div>
+
+          <div class="cs-decision">
+            <div class="decision-label">Decision 2 — One partner, five markets</div>
+            <div class="decision-text">
+              Rather than integrating a separate provider per country, we found a
+              single partner with pre-existing coverage across Argentina, Mexico,
+              Peru, Chile, and Ecuador.
+              <strong>One integration unlocked five markets</strong> — and avoided
+              rebuilding compliance, settlement, and FX conversion from scratch in each.
+            </div>
+          </div>
+
+          <div class="cs-decision">
+            <div class="decision-label">Decision 3 — Run compliance and engineering in parallel</div>
+            <div class="decision-text">
+              Country licensing and payment processor contracts were the longest-lead
+              dependencies on the project. Rather than treating them as a gate,
+              I pulled compliance into the discovery phase so legal and engineering
+              tracks ran concurrently. Mexico and Colombia launched together;
+              Argentina followed 8 weeks later.
+            </div>
+          </div>
+        </div>
+
+        <!-- iv. SOLUTION -->
+        <div class="case-section" id="latam-solution">
+          <div class="num">iv.</div>
+          <h2>What we built</h2>
+          <p>
+            A country-aware deposit flow powered by a global payments partner as the
+            aggregator. The mechanic: the partner accepts a local bank transfer,
+            converts it into a
+            <span class="term" data-def="A digital currency pegged 1:1 to the US dollar — stable in value, widely used in crypto markets for saving and trading.">digital dollar</span>,
+            and credits the user's account — automatically, in one flow.
+          </p>
+          <ul>
+            <li>
+              <strong>Mexico:</strong> SPEI (Mexico's real-time bank transfer system —
+              money arrives in under 30 seconds) as the default.
+              OXXO cash deposit available for users without a bank account.
+            </li>
+            <li>
+              <strong>Colombia:</strong> PSE as the default — the same bank network
+              already used by Bancolombia, Nequi, and Daviplata customers daily.
+            </li>
+            <li>
+              <strong>Argentina:</strong> Standard bank transfer and Mercado Pago wallet
+              (Argentina's most widely-used digital payment app).
+            </li>
+          </ul>
+          <p>
+            Fees were surfaced upfront in the confirmation screen — no surprises at
+            the end. On every primary payment method, our fee matched or beat
+            the leading local competitors.
+          </p>
+        </div>
+
