+      <div class="case-content">
+
+        <!-- Quick context: what is P2P? -->
+        <div style="margin: 0 0 24px; padding: 16px 18px; border: 1px solid var(--line); border-radius: 12px; background: rgba(45,91,255,0.04); display:flex; gap:14px; align-items:flex-start;">
+          <div style="flex:0 0 auto; width:36px; height:36px; border-radius:10px; background:#2D5BFF; color:#fff; display:flex; align-items:center; justify-content:center; font-size:1.05rem;">🤝</div>
+          <div style="min-width:0;">
+            <div style="font-size:0.64rem; font-weight:700; letter-spacing:0.18em; color:#2D5BFF; margin-bottom:4px;">QUICK CONTEXT · WHAT IS A P2P MARKETPLACE?</div>
+            <p style="margin:0; font-size:0.88rem; color:var(--ink-soft); line-height:1.5;">
+              A <strong>P2P (peer-to-peer) marketplace</strong> lets users buy and sell crypto directly with each other using their local currency and bank rails. The exchange acts as escrow, not the counterparty — one user posts an offer, another fills it, and the platform releases the crypto once payment is confirmed. In markets where card on-ramps are expensive or fiat rails are restricted, P2P is often <em>the primary way users get into crypto</em>.
+            </p>
+          </div>
+        </div>
+
+        <!-- i. WHY THIS MATTERED -->
+        <div class="case-section" id="vouch-context">
+          <div class="num">i.</div>
+          <h2>Why this mattered</h2>
+
+          <div class="cs-disclaimer">Some business figures have been omitted / cannot be shared in actuality per confidentiality obligations.</div>
+
+          <p>
+            Our focus was clear: <strong>drive P2P growth in Southeast Asia</strong>.
+            SEA wasn't just another region — it was, by most public measures, one of
+            the most crypto-active parts of the world, and the structural reasons were
+            obvious once you looked at them:
+          </p>
+
+          <div class="v-research-stats">
+            <div>
+              <div class="v-rstat-val">Top 5</div>
+              <div class="v-rstat-label">Vietnam &amp; Indonesia consistently ranked in the world's top crypto-adoption markets</div>
+              <div class="v-rstat-src">Chainalysis Global Crypto Adoption Index</div>
+            </div>
+            <div>
+              <div class="v-rstat-val">~20%</div>
+              <div class="v-rstat-label">Of Vietnamese adults reported owning or using crypto</div>
+              <div class="v-rstat-src">Statista / Triple-A · public surveys</div>
+            </div>
+            <div>
+              <div class="v-rstat-val">High-friction</div>
+              <div class="v-rstat-label">Card on-ramps were limited or expensive — making P2P the primary way users got in</div>
+              <div class="v-rstat-src">Regional payments landscape</div>
+            </div>
+            <div>
+              <div class="v-rstat-val">$200+</div>
+              <div class="v-rstat-label">CAC per crypto user industry-wide — retention drives the unit economics</div>
+              <div class="v-rstat-src">a16z · public filings</div>
+            </div>
+          </div>
+
+          <p>
+            <strong>Vietnam was already our second-largest market globally</strong> —
+            yet on trading volume, we were still trailing the regional category
+            leaders. That gap wasn't a sign of weak demand; it was a sign of how much
+            headroom was still on the table. If we could close even part of it, the
+            payoff at this scale was substantial.
+          </p>
+          <p>
+            Indonesia and the Philippines had been left behind for a
+            while — we hadn't meaningfully invested in either market.
+            But the market research was hard to argue with: large young
+            populations, mobile-first behaviour, high crypto interest,
+            and competitors already pushing in. The growth potential in
+            both was huge. Together with Vietnam, these were the three
+            SEA markets I focused on first — standing still wasn't an
+            option.
+          </p>
+        </div>
+
+        <!-- ii. PROBLEM -->
+        <div class="case-section" id="vouch-problem">
+          <div class="num">ii.</div>
+          <h2>Problem</h2>
+          <p>
+            The headline number was simple: <strong>first deposits via P2P were
+            weak</strong>. But the actual problem only made sense once we drilled
+            into <em>why</em> — and what we found wasn't a funnel leak, it was a
+            marketplace dynamic.
+          </p>
+
+          <div class="v-diag">
+            <div class="v-diag-card">
+              <div class="v-diag-head">
+                <span class="v-diag-icon">📉</span>
+                <span class="v-diag-num">01 · OBSERVED</span>
+                <span class="v-diag-q">First-deposit conversion via P2P sat well below benchmark.</span>
+              </div>
+              <p class="v-diag-a">
+                Users were signing up and completing KYC — then not funding their
+                account through us. The drop wasn't a UX problem; it was happening
+                <em>after</em> they'd already chosen to be customers.
+              </p>
+            </div>
+
+            <div class="v-diag-card">
+              <div class="v-diag-head">
+                <span class="v-diag-icon">🔍</span>
+                <span class="v-diag-num">02 · BEHAVIOUR</span>
+                <span class="v-diag-q">They were buying elsewhere and transferring crypto in to sell.</span>
+              </div>
+              <p class="v-diag-a">
+                A consistent pattern surfaced: users bought crypto on
+                <strong>competitor exchanges</strong>, then moved the asset over
+                to us to sell. We were getting volume — but mostly as a
+                <em>sell-side venue</em>, losing the buy-side flow that should
+                have been ours.
+              </p>
+            </div>
+
+            <div class="v-diag-card">
+              <div class="v-diag-head">
+                <span class="v-diag-icon">💱</span>
+                <span class="v-diag-num">03 · WHY</span>
+                <span class="v-diag-q">Why? Our P2P rates weren't competitive.</span>
+              </div>
+              <p class="v-diag-a">
+                Buyers got a worse price on our marketplace than they did on
+                regional category leaders. In a fungible product like crypto,
+                <strong>even a small spread is enough to send users elsewhere</strong>.
+              </p>
+            </div>
+
+            <div class="v-diag-card">
+              <div class="v-diag-head">
+                <span class="v-diag-icon">⚙️</span>
+                <span class="v-diag-num">04 · ROOT CAUSE</span>
+                <span class="v-diag-q">And rates weren't competitive because liquidity was too thin.</span>
+              </div>
+              <p class="v-diag-a">
+                Without enough takers to make ads worth posting, merchants
+                couldn't quote aggressive prices. Thin liquidity meant wider
+                spreads, which pushed buyers out, which left us with even thinner
+                liquidity. A classic <strong>cold-start marketplace</strong> stuck
+                in reverse.
+              </p>
+            </div>
+          </div>
+
+          <p style="margin-top:14px;">
+            Drawn out, the marketplace was stuck in the wrong half of its own
+            flywheel — every turn made the next turn worse:
+          </p>
+
+          <div class="v-flywheel" aria-label="Marketplace flywheel running in reverse">
+            <span class="v-fly-node bad v-fly-n1">💧 Low liquidity</span>
+            <span class="v-fly-arrow v-fly-h1">→</span>
+            <span class="v-fly-node bad v-fly-n2">📈 Wider spreads</span>
+            <span class="v-fly-arrow v-fly-h2">→</span>
+            <span class="v-fly-node bad v-fly-n3">💸 Worse rates</span>
+
+            <span class="v-fly-arrow v-fly-v-left">↑</span>
+            <span class="v-fly-arrow v-fly-v-right">↓</span>
+
+            <span class="v-fly-node bad v-fly-n6">📋 Merchants stop posting</span>
+            <span class="v-fly-arrow v-fly-h4">←</span>
+            <span class="v-fly-node bad v-fly-n5">👤 Fewer takers</span>
+            <span class="v-fly-arrow v-fly-h3">←</span>
+            <span class="v-fly-node bad v-fly-n4">🚪 Users buy elsewhere</span>
+          </div>
+          <div class="v-fly-caption">↻ Marketplace flywheel — running in reverse</div>
+
+          <p style="margin-top:22px;">
+            The problem wasn't activation as a number — it was a <strong>cold-start
+            marketplace</strong>. So the brief I set was specific: <strong>be
+            aggressive on incentives to subsidise the rate gap, get takers in
+            volume, and keep them coming back</strong> — not through one-off
+            promos, but through a repeated, programmatic mechanic. More takers
+            would attract more merchants to post ads; more merchants would tighten
+            spreads; tighter spreads would pull more organic demand. The flywheel
+            just needed something to spin it.
+          </p>
+        </div>
+
+        <!-- iii. DEVELOPING THE IDEA -->
+        <div class="case-section" id="vouch-diagnosis">
+          <div class="num">iii.</div>
+          <h2>Developing the idea</h2>
+
+          <p>
+            The flywheel diagnosis defined the brief: a mechanic that could
+            subsidise the rate gap, reward the behaviours that fed liquidity,
+            and pull users back often enough for the loop to compound. The
+            four chapters below walk through how I moved from that brief to a
+            concrete product spec — define the mechanic, validate it, segment
+            the user base, set the build principles.
+          </p>
+
+          <!-- ─── A. Defining the mechanic ─────────────────────────── -->
+          <div class="v-chapter">
+            <div class="v-chapter-tag">A</div>
+            <div>
+              <h3 class="v-chapter-h">Defining the mechanic</h3>
+              <p class="v-chapter-lead">What kind of incentive layer would actually move the flywheel.</p>
+            </div>
+          </div>
+
+          <div class="v-beat">
+            <span class="v-beat-tag">Context</span>
+            <p>
+              Vietnam ranked top-5 globally for crypto adoption; Indonesia
+              and the Philippines were top-10 (Chainalysis 2023). We held
+              ~20% market share across these markets — meaningful, but
+              behind regional leaders with multi-year head starts on brand
+              and liquidity.
+            </p>
+            <p>
+              The product wasn't the gap. Across several rounds of merchant
+              interviews and surveys, the feedback came back consistent:
+              the app was solid, but takers wouldn't trade with us because
+              our prices weren't the most competitive and other exchanges
+              always had more campaigns running.
+            </p>
+            <div style="margin: 14px 0 2px; padding: 14px 16px; border-left: 2px solid var(--accent); background: rgba(0,0,0,0.02); display:grid; gap:14px;">
+              <div>
+                <p style="font-size:0.92rem; color:var(--ink); margin:0 0 4px; font-style:italic;">"Your app is fine. But buyers compare prices first — if I quote at my floor, I still lose to other exchanges most of the time."</p>
+                <p style="font-size:0.78rem; color:var(--ink-soft); margin:0;">— P2P merchant, Vietnam</p>
+              </div>
+              <div>
+                <p style="font-size:0.92rem; color:var(--ink); margin:0 0 4px; font-style:italic;">"Other exchanges always have some promotion running. When my buyers see a voucher there, they switch — it isn't the app, it's the price they end up paying."</p>
+                <p style="font-size:0.78rem; color:var(--ink-soft); margin:0;">— P2P merchant, Indonesia</p>
+              </div>
+              <div>
+                <p style="font-size:0.92rem; color:var(--ink); margin:0 0 4px; font-style:italic;">"I trade on OKX occasionally because there are no fees, but sometimes I go somewhere else because it's cheaper there."</p>
+                <p style="font-size:0.78rem; color:var(--ink-soft); margin:0;">— Taker survey respondent, Philippines</p>
+              </div>
+            </div>
+          </div>
+
+          <div class="v-beat">
+            <span class="v-beat-tag">Approach</span>
+            <p>
+              We weren't lacking in product features — we were lacking in
+              reasons to come back and reasons to stay cheaper. So instead
+              of benchmarking crypto peers, I studied the consumer-tech
+              apps SEA users were already fluent in — Shopee, Grab,
+              Tokopedia. Two mechanics surfaced as the load-bearing
+              retention pattern across all three:
+            </p>
+          </div>
+
+          <div class="v-mechanics">
+            <div class="v-mech-ref">
+              <div class="v-mech-ref-logo">🛒</div>
+              <div>
+                <div class="v-mech-ref-name">Shopee — vouchers</div>
+                <p class="v-mech-ref-desc">
+                  Stackable, time-bound vouchers issued for daily login, first
+                  purchase, and category-specific actions. The wallet is a daily
+                  destination; expiry creates the return loop.
+                </p>
+              </div>
+            </div>
+            <div class="v-mech-ref">
+              <div class="v-mech-ref-logo">🛵</div>
+              <div>
+                <div class="v-mech-ref-name">Grab — points + rewards</div>
+                <p class="v-mech-ref-desc">
+                  GrabRewards points earned on every transaction, redeemable for
+                  discount vouchers, partner deals, and tier perks. Behaviour in,
+                  reward out — every ride builds toward the next claim.
+                </p>
+              </div>
+            </div>
+          </div>
+
+          <div class="v-beat">
+            <span class="v-beat-tag">Finding</span>
+            <p>
+              The mechanics differed (vouchers vs. points, expiry vs. tier
+              progression) but the underlying pattern was identical: an
+              incentive layer wrapped around the core transaction, turning
+              each interaction into a small commitment loop — do this, get
+              this, come back to claim more. Different product, same growth
+              psychology.
+            </p>
+          </div>
+
+          <!-- ─── B. Validating the hypothesis ─────────────────────── -->
+          <div class="v-chapter">
+            <div class="v-chapter-tag">B</div>
+            <div>
+              <h3 class="v-chapter-h">Validating the hypothesis</h3>
+              <p class="v-chapter-lead">A platform-scale build needs validation before scoping. I pulled it from our own data and direct user interviews.</p>
+            </div>
+          </div>
+
+          <div class="v-beat">
+            <span class="v-beat-tag">Approach</span>
+            <p>
+              The mechanic looked right on paper. Before committing to a
+              multi-market platform build, I wanted to validate it against
+              our own user behaviour and direct interview feedback — not
+              just analogy to adjacent consumer-tech.
+            </p>
+          </div>
+
+          <div class="v-insights">
+            <div class="v-insight">
+              <div class="v-insight-num">01 / DATA</div>
+              <div class="v-insight-title">Activation collapses after the first week</div>
+              <p class="v-insight-body">
+                The majority of users who eventually traded did so within
+                the <strong>first 7 days</strong> of signup. Beyond that
+                window, activation probability dropped sharply — users who
+                hadn't traded within 7 days were roughly <strong>5×</strong>
+                less likely to ever do so. Pre-launch activation in SEA
+                averaged <strong>19%</strong> across VN/ID/PH — and email/push
+                reactivation barely moved the number, because there was no
+                real incentive for users to come back.
+              </p>
+            </div>
+
+            <div class="v-insight">
+              <div class="v-insight-num">02 / INTERVIEWS</div>
+              <div class="v-insight-title">Users were already rate-shopping</div>
+              <p class="v-insight-body">
+                Initial validation: in-depth interviews + 412 survey
+                responses across VN/ID/PH.
+                <strong>&gt;80%</strong> held accounts on 2+ exchanges and
+                rate-shopped per trade. <strong>64%</strong> cited
+                rates / fees as the top decision factor on a given day.
+                <strong>41%</strong> of new users said a promo or referral
+                nudged their first deposit. The behaviour we needed already
+                existed — vouchers had to win those decision moments.
+              </p>
+            </div>
+
+            <div class="v-insight">
+              <div class="v-insight-num">03 / CONTEXT</div>
+              <div class="v-insight-title">SEA users are already trained on this</div>
+              <p class="v-insight-body">
+                SEA's largest consumer apps — Shopee, Tokopedia, Grab — all
+                build retention around vouchers and points programs
+                (Bain &amp; Google e-Conomy SEA 2023). Users in our research
+                expected, not just tolerated, the mechanic: time-limited
+                claims, stackable rewards, visible expiry. The habit was
+                already trained.
+              </p>
+            </div>
+
+            <div class="v-insight">
+              <div class="v-insight-num">04 / SYNTHESIS</div>
+              <div class="v-insight-title">Vouchers fit — as a loop, not a discount</div>
+              <p class="v-insight-body">
+                The mechanic was a fit, with one caveat: it only compounds
+                if wired as a behaviour-triggered loop. As a one-off promo
+                it produces a spike and decays. As triggered, owned
+                infrastructure it builds a habit.
+              </p>
+            </div>
+          </div>
+
+          <div class="v-beat">
+            <span class="v-beat-tag">Conclusion</span>
+            <p>
+              Vouchers were the right mechanic. The question moved from
+              <em>whether</em> to <em>how</em> — specifically, how to deploy
+              them when the same voucher means very different things to
+              different users.
+            </p>
+          </div>
+
+          <!-- ─── C. Segmenting users by lifecycle stage ──────────── -->
+          <div class="v-chapter">
+            <div class="v-chapter-tag">C</div>
+            <div>
+              <h3 class="v-chapter-h">Segmenting users by lifecycle stage</h3>
+              <p class="v-chapter-lead">A single voucher couldn't do the right job across three taker-side segments.</p>
+            </div>
+          </div>
+
+          <div class="v-beat">
+            <span class="v-beat-tag">Initial design</span>
+            <p>
+              First sketch was a one-off discount campaign — a single
+              market-wide voucher drop to subsidise the rate gap. It would
+              ship, but I wasn't confident on ROI: a flat discount sent to
+              everyone treats a new user and a lapsed trader the same, and
+              the spend doesn't compound after the window closes.
+            </p>
+          </div>
+
+          <div class="v-beat">
+            <span class="v-beat-tag">Research method</span>
+            <p>
+              I scoped the study to takers — the side that drives volume
+              growth and where subsidy economics actually work — and ran
+              cohort analysis on 12 months of internal data alongside
+              stratified user interviews (n=24 across VN/ID/PH, sampled
+              across new / lapsed / active sub-tier) to see whether takers
+              behaved as one cohort or several.
+            </p>
+          </div>
+
+          <div class="v-beat">
+            <span class="v-beat-tag">Finding · what each segment needed</span>
+            <p>
+              Three taker-side segments fell out of the data, each with a
+              distinct job-to-be-done:
+            </p>
+          </div>
+
+          <div class="v-needs">
+            <div class="v-need">
+              <div class="v-need-seg">🆕 New users</div>
+              <p class="v-need-quote">"I downloaded it, but I'm not sure what to buy first — and the price seems higher than other apps."</p>
+              <p class="v-need-line">
+                <strong>Need:</strong> low-friction trigger to make a
+                first deposit; subsidy must close the rate gap visibly.
+              </p>
+            </div>
+            <div class="v-need">
+              <div class="v-need-seg">😴 Lapsed</div>
+              <p class="v-need-quote">"I haven't opened it in a while. I forgot it was there until the notification came."</p>
+              <p class="v-need-line">
+                <strong>Need:</strong> re-entry trigger tied to dormancy
+                threshold — a discount alone doesn't recall the app.
+              </p>
+            </div>
+            <div class="v-need">
+              <div class="v-need-seg">⚡ Active · sub-tier</div>
+              <p class="v-need-quote">"I trade on OKX occasionally, because it doesnt have any fees. But sometimes I go somewhere else cause its cheaper also."</p>
+              <p class="v-need-line">
+                <strong>Need:</strong> volume-tier rebate that compounds
+                with usage; price-sensitive but already engaged.
+              </p>
+            </div>
+          </div>
+
+          <div class="v-beat">
+            <span class="v-beat-tag">Why a rule engine — not multiple campaigns</span>
+            <p>
+              Each segment needed its own trigger, voucher type, and
+              eligibility rule — and we needed to ship across VN, ID, and
+              PH. Running this as parallel campaigns meant a code change
+              for every tweak: iteration speed wouldn't keep up with what
+              we'd learn in-market.
+            </p>
+            <p>
+              A rule engine fixed that. Set the trigger, the voucher, and
+              the budget in a config — the engine handles the rest. Growth
+              ships new rules without engineering, and the same setup
+              works for any market.
+            </p>
+          </div>
+
+          <p style="margin-top:18px; font-size:0.86rem; color:var(--ink-soft); font-style:italic;">
+            Same engine. Different rules per segment, per market, per
+            campaign. Adding a new rule is config, not code.
+          </p>
+
+          <!-- ─── D. Setting product principles ──────────────────── -->
+          <div class="v-chapter">
+            <div class="v-chapter-tag">D</div>
+            <div>
+              <h3 class="v-chapter-h">Setting product principles</h3>
+              <p class="v-chapter-lead">Three product calls that shaped how the engine got built.</p>
+            </div>
+          </div>
+
+          <p style="margin-top:14px;">
+            Each principle was a deliberate trade-off against a real
+            alternative — and each is the place a worse version of this
+            project would have taken the easier path.
+          </p>
+
+          <div class="v-principles">
+            <div class="v-principle">
+              <div class="v-principle-num">01</div>
+              <div class="v-principle-body">
+                <div class="v-principle-title">Build an engine, not a campaign</div>
+                <p class="v-principle-text">
+                  Marketing wanted a single seasonal promo for SEA. I pushed back
+                  and scoped a <strong>rules-based voucher engine</strong> instead —
+                  supporting fee discounts, USDT bonuses, and cashback rebates as
+                  configurable voucher types. Same engineering effort, durable
+                  infrastructure.
+                </p>
+              </div>
+            </div>
+
+            <div class="v-principle">
+              <div class="v-principle-num">02</div>
+              <div class="v-principle-body">
+                <div class="v-principle-title">Trigger on behaviour, not signup</div>
+                <p class="v-principle-text">
+                  Issuing vouchers at signup attracts deal-hunters with low intent.
+                  We tied issuance to <strong>specific behaviours</strong> — first
+                  deposit, first trade, dormancy thresholds — so each voucher both
+                  rewarded an action and nudged the next one.
+                </p>
+                <p class="v-principle-text" style="margin-top:8px;">
+                  This was also how we kept the unit economics in check. The goal wasn't
+                  sign-ups — it was converting takers into active traders. By gating
+                  vouchers behind completing a trading activity, every voucher claimed
