+        <!-- iii. THE HARD QUESTION -->
+        <div class="case-section" id="ads-question">
+          <div class="num">iii.</div>
+          <h2>Problem</h2>
+
+          <p class="cs-lede">"If we let merchants buy the top spot — what stops them from exploiting the takers who click on them?"</p>
+
+          <p>
+            This was the question that had to be answered before anything else. Paid placement in a
+            two-sided marketplace has a well-known failure mode: the party that pays can capture
+            visibility at the expense of the party that doesn't. In retail it's sponsored results that
+            are worse products. In P2P, it would be sponsored merchants offering bad rates to takers
+            who reasonably assumed the top result was the best deal.
+          </p>
+
+          <p>Two failure modes shaped every design decision that followed:</p>
+
+          <div class="cs-risk-pair">
+            <div class="cs-risk-card">
+              <div style="font-size:0.65rem; font-weight:700; text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:0.07em; color:#D97706; margin-bottom:8px;">Failure mode A</div>
+              <div style="font-weight:700; font-size:0.92rem; margin-bottom:6px;">Pay-to-win</div>
+              <p style="font-size:0.8rem; margin:0; line-height:1.55;">Rich merchants dominate the top regardless of rate quality. Takers lose. Merchant trust erodes. The marketplace degrades.</p>
+            </div>
+            <div class="cs-risk-card">
+              <div style="font-size:0.65rem; font-weight:700; text-transform:uppercase; letter-spacing:0.07em; color:#D97706; margin-bottom:8px;">Failure mode B</div>
+              <div style="font-weight:700; font-size:0.92rem; margin-bottom:6px;">Rate exploitation</div>
+              <p style="font-size:0.8rem; margin:0; line-height:1.55;">Sponsored merchants post uncompetitive rates. Takers trust the top result and get a bad deal. NPS tanks. Regulatory risk rises.</p>
+            </div>
+          </div>
+
+          <p>
+            The product could only exist if both failure modes were designed against
+            <em>structurally</em> — not as policy or moderation, but baked into the core mechanics.
+          </p>
+        </div>
+
+        <!-- iv. MAKING IT FAIR -->
+        <div class="case-section" id="ads-fair">
+          <div class="num">iv.</div>
+          <h2>Approach</h2>
+
+          <p>Three guardrails. Each one addressed a specific way the system could break.</p>
+
+          <div class="cs-guardrail">
+            <div class="cs-guardrail-head">
+              <div class="cs-guardrail-n" style="display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-weight:700;font-size:0.78rem;">1</div>
+              <div>
+                <div style="font-weight:700; font-size:0.88rem;">Auction-based bidding</div>
